               <interp inst="t18571026-1120" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18571026"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18571026-1120" type="date" value="18571026"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18571026-1120-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1120-18571026 t18571026-1120-offence-1 t18571026-1120-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18571026-1120-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-1120-18571026 t18571026-1120-offence-1 t18571026-1120-verdict-2"></join>
               <p>1120. <persName id="def1-1120-18571026" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1120-18571026" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1120-18571026" type="age" value="26"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1120-18571026" type="surname" value="DENBY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1120-18571026" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">HENRY DENBY</hi> (26)</persName> and <persName id="def2-1120-18571026" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-1120-18571026" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1120-18571026" type="age" value="25"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1120-18571026" type="surname" value="HOLBROOK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1120-18571026" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN HOLBROOK</hi> (25)</persName>, <rs id="t18571026-1120-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18571026-1120-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18571026-1120-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>Stealing three curtains, and other goods, the property of <persName id="t18571026-name-704" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-704" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-704" type="surname" value="HALWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-704" type="given" value="ANN MARY"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18571026-1120-offence-1 t18571026-name-704"></join>Ann Mary Halwell</persName> and <persName id="t18571026-name-705" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-705" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-705" type="surname" value="WRIGHT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-705" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18571026-1120-offence-1 t18571026-name-705"></join>Robert Wright</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-706" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-706" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-706" type="surname" value="HALWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-706" type="given" value="ANN MARY"></interp>ANN MARY HALWELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am cook to Miss Hall, of Leyton. On 30th Sept., I had been washing some articles—I hung them out to dry between 4 and 5 o'clock, in the afternoon, in Miss Hall's drying ground, adjoining the lawn—these (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) are the things; some are Miss Hall's, some mine, and some the coachman's; some have not been found.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SHARPE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When did you miss them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> At a quarter to 6 o'clock—the church clock was facing me, and I looked at it; it is about four minutes' walk—I do not know how far I walk in that time—it was near the end of September, but I can always see the clock—I know these things belong to Wright, because I have washed for him oc<lb></lb>casionally</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185710260176"></xptr>
               <p>for six years; I also helped to make them—I know my own work.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-707" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-707" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-707" type="surname" value="WRIGHT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-707" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT WRIGHT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am coachman to Miss Hall. I saw these things safe at 5 o'clock, on the day in question—I missed them at a quarter to 6 o'clock—the lines had been cut, and taken away—these scarves are mine.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Were you examined before to-day? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, at Ilford; there is no mark on the scarves by which I know them—they are exactly like mine—they were found in Mr. Charrington's Park.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-708" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-708" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-708" type="surname" value="CHOAT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-708" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES CHOAT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a labourer, living at Stratford. On 30th Sept, I saw the prisoners together at Leyton—that was a quarter before 5 o'clock—Denby had a bag with him—there was nothing in it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> What were you doing? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I was carrying a pail to fetch water; I spoke to Denby, but he made no answer—I had seen him a great many times—I stopped on the road, and these two went up to<lb></lb>wards Miss Hall's place; I took particular notice of the bag, because it was slung over his shoulder; and Holbrook asked me in the morning, whether I had seen anything him—I had known Holbrook before—I said, at the Police Court, I had known him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-709" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-709" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-709" type="surname" value="WILDING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-709" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WILDING</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an appraiser and house agent, living at Leyton. On 30th Sept., I was standing at my garden gate, near Miss Hall's, about 5 o'clock—a gentleman came, and spoke to me—in consequence of what he said, I looked towards Miss Hall's—I there saw some things on the line, and, in an instant, the things went down, as if the line had been cut; presently, I saw two men come away directly from the spot; they went through the church-yard, towards Leyton—I went up the pathway, towards Miss Hall's drying ground, and saw the two men come through; one had a bag—I know the jacket one had on—the prisoner Denby had on that jacket he has now; Holbrook followed him—I only saw they had a bag with something in it; I then went round the path, towards Leyton, to look for a constable, so as to come round and meet them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you ever see Denby before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have seen both of them; all this occurred in a very little while; the nearest man was about two hundred or three hundred yards off; it might not be so far—I did not see them after this until they were in custody at Ilford.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-710" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-710" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-710" type="surname" value="NEALE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-710" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD NEALE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a cow keeper, at Leyton, near to Miss Hall. On 30th Sept., my attention was called to the two prisoners; I had seen them before—Holbrook was pulling the clothes off the line—Denby was kneeling down, putting them in the bag—I was standing at a window—they then went towards Leyton Churchyard—I then gave information to the police.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Do you know Denby?. <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; he goes about col<lb></lb>lecting rags and bones—I was not near the last witness, nor did I speak to him—there was a field between me and Miss Hall's, about 200 yards—I am sure Holbrook is the man who was taking the things off the line—I was examined before the Magistrate at Ilford—I could not swear to the man then—I might have seen Holbrook before; Denby I have seen come round for the rags and bones—when before the Magistrate, I did not "only believe" that Holbrook was the man who was taking the clothes off the line—it might be that I never saw him before, but I know him—he was the smaller man of the two—I did not see him afterwards until he was in cu<lb></lb>tody at Ilford.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-711" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-711" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-711" type="surname" value="PORTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-711" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS PORTER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a coal dealer, living at Stratford. On 30th Sept. I was driving a horse and van near the Blackbird public house, at Leyton;</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185710260177"></xptr>
               <p>I was driving towards Stratford—I saw Holbrook on the road—he came up to me—I stopped the horse—he then stepped back, and beckoned the other prisoner—he came up in a few minutes with the bag—they put the bag in the waggon, got up, and rode as far as the Castle inn, at Stratford—they there got down and walked away.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> At the time Holbrook came up, did you notice the other man? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, I did not for the moment—Denby was carrying the bag—there was another man got into the waggon at the same time—he was carrying a basket of china, and the prisoners helped to lift it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-712" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-712" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-712" type="surname" value="HUNTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-712" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE HUNTER</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">Policeman, N</hi> 357). On 2nd Oct. I took Holbrook into custody, in East Street, Stratford. I told him it was for a robbery—he asked me where it was, and I told him at Leyton, on Wednesday—he said, "I was not there on Wednesday"—I then took him to the Waltham<lb></lb>stow station.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you tell him it was for stealing linen in the first instance? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did not; I told him it was for a robbery at Leyton, at Miss Hall's—where I took him was about two miles from Leyton.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-713" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-713" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-713" type="surname" value="CARPENTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-713" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES CARPENTER</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">Policeman, N</hi> 477). I found the prisoner Denby at Stratford—I asked him whew he was on Wednesday last—he said, "I was at home"—I said, "Be careful; I am a police constable; I am going to take him into custody"—he said, "What for?"—I told him for a robbery of wet linen at Leyton—he said, "I was at home on Wednesday"—he afterwards said, "I was at Leyton on Saturday last"—after that, he said he was there on Tuesday, but was at home Wednesday and Thursday—I asked him who was with him—he said, "Chitty Holbrook."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-714" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-714" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-714" type="surname" value="HALWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-714" type="given" value="ANN MARY"></interp>ANN MARY HALWELL</persName>
                  </hi>. <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> This (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) is the sort of line on which the things were; the other part is left on the post.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-715" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-715" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-715" type="surname" value="WRIGHT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-715" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT WRIGHT</persName>
                  </hi>. <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I found these things in Mr. Charrington's park, about 8 o'clock, on 1st Oct.—the gardener told me of them, and found them just inside the park, near the walk through the churchyard—they are not all the things that were lost.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">DENBY</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18571026-1120-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-1120-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-1120-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">HOLBROOK</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18571026-1120-verdict-2" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-1120-verdict-2" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-1120-verdict-2" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>.</p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">The prisoners were further charged with having been before convicted</hi>).</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18571026-name-716" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-716" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-716" type="surname" value="BENTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18571026-name-716" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH BENTON</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">Policeman, K</hi> 381) I produce the certificate—(<hi rend="italic">one of these certified the conviction of Henry Revell in May</hi>, 1848, <hi rend="italic">of Larceny; and the other, the conviction of John Holbrook, of Larceny</hi>)—I was present at the trial of Henry Revell—Denby is the person so described—he has been getting an honest living since 1848—Holbrook is the person mentioned in the second certificate.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">DENBY</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
GUILTY</hi>.—<hi rend="italic">
